[1] Bayoud disease - Arab Gulf region
Date: Mon 4 Aug 2008
Source: Arabian Business [edited]
<http://www.arabianbusiness.com/526328-planting-expert-warns-of-new-palm-disease>


Planting expert warns of new palm disease
-----------------------------------------
An expert has warned that growing demand for
Moroccan date palms could expose the GCC [Gulf
Cooperation Council -- Bahrain, Qatar, Kuwait,
Oman, Saudi Arabia, and United Arab Emirates] to
a disease that can decimate date palm
populations. Trends to import species of palms
from Morocco were increasing the likelihood of
the fusarium fungus disease coming into the
region. The fungus triggers bayoud disease, which
causes the leaves on one side of the palm to dry,
followed by the death of the tree. First
discovered around 100 years ago in Morocco, there
is no known treatment for the disease.

"[The fungus] has destroyed more than half of the
palm groves in Morocco and has spread easterly
through the trade of offshoots to Algeria and
reached the east of Africa," said Franck
Marionnet, general manager of palm nursery at
Wathba Marionnet. "There is nowadays a trend to
plant in the Gulf a variety from Morocco called
medjool, and it is risky to import offshoots."

Previously, the Gulf has been safe from the
fungus because the medjool has had limited appeal
for the local date market. However increasing
numbers are being imported commercially because
medjool dates are favoured for export to the more
lucrative European and US markets. [Bayoud
disease] could potentially destroy palm trees in
the Gulf region. According to Marionnet, palms
tend to be selected on the basis of cost, meaning
'safeÂ’' palms grown from tissue cultures are
rarely used.

[Byline: James Boley]

