[2] Maize smut - Yemen
Date: Wed 13 Aug 2008
Source: UN Office for the Coordination of
Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA), Integrated Regional
Information Networks (IRIN) News [edited]
<http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=79794>


Ministry issues warning on maize smut
-------------------------------------
The Ministry of Agriculture and Irrigation (MAI)
has warned farmers about a fungus known as "maize
smut" and asked them to use seeds that do not
contain the fungus. The warning comes as the
maize cultivation season gets under way.

Mansour al-Aqel, director-general of the MAI's
agricultural information department, said maize
smut appeared in Yemen many years ago due to
farmers not selecting clean seeds. The fungus
only attacks maize. "The spread of the disease
depends on the farmers themselves," he told IRIN,
adding, "there are improved seeds that are
treated in a way that can fight the fungus."

Al-Aqel said if farmers do not select improved
and clean spikes, the losses caused by maize smut
could be big. "Losses differ from one farmer to
another. The lazy farmer would lose the most. On
some farms, losses could run to 60 percent. If
the fungus is left untreated, then it causes
higher losses," he said. According to al-Aqel,
when the maize crop is infected, black spores
replace the kernels, making the plants useless.

Figure: Maize smut grows down the silks to the
kernels and causes galls on the ears
<http://www.irinnews.org/PhotoDetail.aspx?ImageId=2008081311>

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Dates are an extremely important subsistence
crop in most of the desert regions. Bayoud
disease is one of the most serious diseases of
this crop in North Africa and has destroyed
around two thirds of date palms in Morocco over
the last century. It is caused by the fungus
_Fusarium oxysporum_ f. sp. _albedinis_. Symptoms
include bleaching and subsequent drying off of
fronds, followed by death of the tree. The fungus
can survive for several years on plant debris or
in the ground. Bayoud kills many of the popular
older cultivars and has led to a major decline in
production wherever it is present. Disease
management relies on exclusion, phytosanitation,
and the use of new resistant cultivars, which are
being developed. Another strain of the pathogen,
_F. o._ f. sp. _canariensis_ causes a similar
disease in ornamental date species in the USA.
Related species such as _F. proliferatum_ in
Saudi Arabia and _F. moniliforme_ have been
reported to cause similar diseases.

Maize smut is caused by the fungus _Ustilago
maydis_. Tumour-like swellings are formed which
can appear on all growing parts of the plant. If
the collar is attacked plants may die, and smut
balls on cobs replace kernels. The yield of these
cobs is very low and they may be toxic to
livestock. The fungus survives in the soil and
crop debris, and spores are rain- and windborne.
The disease is favoured by hot, dry conditions.
Several disease cycles may occur in one crop
leading to severe epidemics. Disease management
includes cultural methods, phytosanitation, and
use of resistant cultivars. Seed treatment is not
considered effective because the pathogen is not
seed-borne. If over several seasons smut-infected
plants are removed from the fields before spores
are released, the amount of infection in an area
can be reduced.

